      "acceptanceCriteria": "An independent analyst must repeat key simulation runs from documentation alone; discrepancies must be within 2% of hemolysis index to confirm reproducibility and absence of user-induced error.",
      "rationale": "No independent reproducibility exercise was conducted. Simulation setup documentation was insufficient for an independent analyst to reproduce results. Flagged as epistemic gap; achieved level 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The power-law hemolysis model must be assessed against alternative constitutive models (e.g., strain-based, threshold models) with documented justification for model selection at the target operating conditions.",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty was not assessed. The power-law Giersiepen-Wurzinger model was used without comparison to alternative hemolysis models. At MRL 5 this constitutes a critical epistemic gap; achieved level 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters (viscosity, density, hemolysis exponents) must have documented uncertainty distributions derived from literature or measurement, propagated through Monte Carlo UQ to bound QOI uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Although Monte Carlo UQ was nominally performed, input distributions for hemolysis model exponents were not grounded in experimental data and were assigned as uniform ±10% without justification. Flagged as epistemic gap; achieved level 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Biological variability in blood rheology across donor samples must be characterised and its effect on hemolysis predictions quantified through sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Inter-donor variability in blood rheology was not characterised. All experiments used a single bovine blood batch. Biological variability contribution to hemolysis prediction uncertainty is unknown. Flagged as epistemic gap; achieved level 1."
